Ukraine\">Ukraine<\/a>). He later immigrated to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_British_Mandate_of_Palestine\" title=\"The British Mandate of Palestine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">the British Mandate of Palestine<\/a>, and died in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jerusalem\" title=\"Jerusalem\">Jerusalem<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Israel\" title=\"Israel\">Israel<\/a>.<\/p><p>His works deal with the conflict between the traditional <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jew\" title=\"Jew\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Jewish<\/a> life and language and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Modern_world\" title=\"Modern world\" class=\"mw-redirect\">modern world<\/a>. They also attempt to recapture the fading traditions of the European <i><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Shtetl\" title=\"Shtetl\">shtetl<\/a><\/i> (village). In a wider context, he also contributed to broadening the characteristic conception of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Narrator\" title=\"Narrator\" class=\"mw-redirect\">narrator<\/a>'s role in literature. Agnon shared the Nobel Prize with the poet <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nelly_Sachs\" title=\"Nelly Sachs\">Nelly Sachs<\/a> in 1966.<\/p>","name":"Shmuel Yosef Agnon","place_of_birth":"Buczacz ,  Galicia  ( Buchach ,  Ukraine )","place_of_death":"Jerusalem ,  Israel","text":"Shmuel Yosef Agnon ,  born in what was then Austria-Hungary, now Ukraine , Literature, 1966","year":1966.0}